snippet.textDisplay:
MatPat, you seem to be forgetting that Simon in the first movie didn't act out of righteousness to show the truth, he did it because he wanted the throne, which leads to question what other things he was willing to do in order to secure the throne/have power for himself.


I know you say that Sinom is more capable because he knows economy but, in reality, there are presidents who know economics (like Rafael Correa) and still sent their countries to massive debt and to near economic crisis. Knowing economy isn't a guarantee that the ruler will be successful or is well intended.


The same way, he isn't trusted in the second movie BECAUSE of how he tried to do anything he could to get the throne, rule of politics Mat, never put someone who backstabbed you in a position of power (and handling the economy of a country IS a position of power) after all, did Simon do anything that showed he was worth the trust? Only after he lost everything apparently, and I say 'apparently' because I haven't watched the movies, I'm just saying all of this by using historical/political references and applying them to the theory you are providing.


And that isn't without talking what kind of government the movie has (it implies an absolute monarchy but the monarchs in Europe are still an institution in Constitutional Monarchies) because the scenes you showed never had the citizens blaming the king for the economic recession, just asking for solutions.


Not gonna argue about whether or not the king or the MC are nice people because they do not seem to be capable people, I just wanted to focus on you saying Simon was the one that had to rule.
